[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] The **finite volume method** (**FVM**) is a method for representing and evaluating partial differential equations in the form of algebraic equations.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] In the finite volume method, volume integrals in a partial differential equation that contain a divergence term are converted to surface integrals, using the divergence theorem.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] These terms are then evaluated as fluxes at the surfaces of each finite volume.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Because the flux entering a given volume is identical to that leaving the adjacent volume, these methods are conservative.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Another advantage of the finite volume method is that it is easily formulated to allow for unstructured meshes.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] The method is used in many computational fluid dynamics packages.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] "Finite volume" refers to the small volume surrounding each node point on a mesh.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Finite volume methods can be compared and contrasted with the finite difference methods, which approximate derivatives using nodal values, or finite element methods, which create local approximations of a solution using local data, and construct a global approximation by stitching them together.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] In contrast a finite volume method evaluates exact expressions for the *average* value of the solution over some volume, and uses this data to construct approximations of the solution within cells.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Here, $\rho =\rho \left(x,t\right)$ represents the state variable and $f=f\left(\rho \left(x,t\right)\right)$ represents the flux or flow of $\rho$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Conventionally, positive f represents flow to the right while negative f represents flow to the left.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] If we assume that equation (**1**) represents a flowing medium of constant area, we can sub-divide the spatial domain, x , into *finite volumes* or *cells* with cell centers indexed as i .
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] where $x_{i-1/2}$ and $x_{i+1/2}$ represent locations of the upstream and downstream faces or edges respectively of the $i^{\text{th}}$ cell.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] We assume that $f\$ is well behaved and that we can reverse the order of integration.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Also, recall that flow is normal to the unit area of the cell.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] where values for the edge fluxes, $f_{i\pm 1/2}$ , can be reconstructed by interpolation or extrapolation of the cell averages.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Equation (**7**) is *exact* for the volume averages; i.e., no approximations have been made during its derivation.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] This method can also be applied to a 2D situation by considering the north and south faces along with the east and west faces around a node.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Here, $\mathbf {u}$ represents a vector of states and $\mathbf {f}$ represents the corresponding flux tensor.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Again we can sub-divide the spatial domain into finite volumes or cells.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] where $S_{i}$ represents the total surface area of the cell and ${\mathbf {n} }$ is a unit vector normal to the surface and pointing outward.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] So, finally, we are able to present the general result equivalent to (**8**), i.e.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Again, values for the edge fluxes can be reconstructed by interpolation or extrapolation of the cell averages.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] The actual numerical scheme will depend upon problem geometry and mesh construction.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] MUSCL reconstruction is often used in high resolution schemes where shocks or discontinuities are present in the solution.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] Finite volume schemes are conservative as cell averages change through the edge fluxes.
[src:finite-volume-method/finite-volume-method] In other words, *one cell's loss is always another cell's gain*!
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] Note that flux limiters are also referred to as **slope limiters** because they both have the same mathematical form, and both have the effect of limiting the solution gradient near shocks or discontinuities.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] In general, the term flux limiter is used when the limiter acts on system *fluxes*, and slope limiter is used when the limiter acts on system *states* (like pressure, velocity etc.).
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] The main idea behind the construction of flux limiter schemes is to limit the spatial derivatives to realistic values – for scientific and engineering problems this usually means physically realisable and meaningful values.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] They are used in high resolution schemes for solving problems described by PDEs and only come into operation when sharp wave fronts are present.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] For smoothly changing waves, the flux limiters do not operate and the spatial derivatives can be represented by higher order approximations without introducing spurious oscillations.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] The limiter function is constrained to be greater than or equal to zero, i.e., $\phi \ (r)\geq 0$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] Therefore, when the limiter is equal to zero (sharp gradient, opposite slopes or zero gradient), the flux is represented by a *low resolution scheme*.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] Similarly, when the limiter is equal to 1 (smooth solution), it is represented by a *high resolution scheme*.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] The various limiters have differing switching characteristics and are selected according to the particular problem and solution scheme.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] No particular limiter has been found to work well for all problems, and a particular choice is usually made on a trial and error basis.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] This is a desirable property as it ensures that the limiting actions for forward and backward gradients operate in the same way.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] Unless indicated to the contrary, the above limiter functions are second order TVD.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] This means that they are designed such that they pass through a certain region of the solution, known as the TVD region, in order to guarantee stability of the scheme.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] The admissible limiter region for second-order TVD schemes is shown in the *Sweby Diagram* opposite, and plots showing limiter functions overlaid onto the TVD region are shown below.
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] In this image, plots for the Osher and Sweby limiters have been generated using $\beta =1.5$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/flux-limiter] An additional limiter that has an interesting form is the van-Leer's one-parameter family of minmod limiters.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] In numerical analysis and computational fluid dynamics, **Godunov's scheme** is a conservative numerical scheme, suggested by Sergei Godunov in 1959, for solving partial differential equations.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] One can think of this method as a conservative finite volume method which solves exact, or approximate Riemann problems at each inter-cell boundary.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] In its basic form, Godunov's method is first order accurate in both space and time, yet can be used as a base scheme for developing higher-order methods.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] Godunov's method replaces the time integral of each $\int _{t^{n}}^{t^{n+1}}f(q(t,x_{i-1/2}))\,dt$ with a forward Euler method which yields a fully discrete update formula for each of the unknowns $Q_{i}^{n}$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] For consistency, one assumes that $f^{\downarrow }(q_{l},q_{r})=f(q_{l})\quad {\text{ if }}\quad q_{l}=q_{r},$ and that $f^{\downarrow }$ is increasing in the first argument, and decreasing in the second argument.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] For scalar problems where $f'(q)>0$ , one can use the simple Upwind scheme, which defines $f^{\downarrow }(q_{l},q_{r})=f(q_{l})$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] Obtain the solution for the local Riemann problem at the cell interfaces.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] This is the only physical step of the whole procedure.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] The discontinuities at the interfaces are resolved in a superposition of waves satisfying locally the conservation equations.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] The original Godunov method is based upon the exact solution of the Riemann problems.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] However, approximate solutions can be applied as an alternative.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] Average the state variables after a time interval ${\Delta t}\,$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] The state variables obtained after Step 2 are averaged over each cell defining a new piecewise constant approximation resulting from the wave propagation during the time interval ${\Delta t}\,$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] To be consistent, the time interval ${\Delta t}\,$ should be limited such that the waves emanating from an interface do not interact with waves created at the adjacent interfaces.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] Otherwise the situation inside a cell would be influenced by interacting Riemann problems.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] This leads to the CFL condition $|a_{\max }|\Delta t<\Delta x/2\,$ where $|a_{\max }|\,$ is the maximum wave speed obtained from the cell eigenvalue(s) of the local *Jacobian matrix*.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] The first and third steps are solely of a numerical nature and can be considered as a *projection stage*, independent of the second, physical step, the *evolution stage*.
[src:finite-volume-method/godunov-s-scheme] Therefore, they can be modified without influencing the physical input, for instance by replacing the piecewise constant approximation by a piecewise linear variation inside each cell, leading to the definition of second-order space-accurate schemes, such as the MUSCL scheme.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] In the study of partial differential equations, the **MUSCL scheme** is a finite volume method that can provide highly accurate numerical solutions for a given system, even in cases where the solutions exhibit shocks, discontinuities, or large gradients.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] MUSCL stands for *Monotonic Upstream-centered Scheme for Conservation Laws* (van Leer, 1979), and the term was introduced in a seminal paper by Bram van Leer (van Leer, 1979).
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] In this paper he constructed the first *high-order*, *total variation diminishing* (TVD) scheme where he obtained second order spatial accuracy.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The idea is to replace the piecewise constant approximation of Godunov's scheme by reconstructed states, derived from cell-averaged states obtained from the previous time-step.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] For each cell, slope limited, reconstructed left and right states are obtained and used to calculate fluxes at the cell boundaries (edges).
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] These fluxes can, in turn, be used as input to a *Riemann solver*, following which the solutions are averaged and used to advance the solution in time.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Alternatively, the fluxes can be used in *Riemann-solver-free* schemes, which are basically Rusanov-like schemes.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Where u represents a state variable and F represents a flux variable.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The basic scheme of Godunov uses piecewise constant approximations for each cell, and results in a first-order upwind discretisation of the above problem with cell centres indexed as i .
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This basic scheme is not able to handle shocks or sharp discontinuities as they tend to become smeared.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] An example of this effect is shown in the diagram opposite, which illustrates a 1D advective equation with a step wave propagating to the right.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The simulation was carried out with a mesh of 200 cells and used a 4th order Runge–Kutta time integrator (RK4).
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] To provide higher resolution of discontinuities, Godunov's scheme can be extended to use piecewise linear approximations of each cell, which results in a *central difference* scheme that is *second-order* accurate in space.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Although the above second-order scheme provides greater accuracy for smooth solutions, it is not a total variation diminishing (TVD) scheme and introduces spurious oscillations into the solution where discontinuities or shocks are present.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] An example of this effect is shown in the diagram opposite, which illustrates a 1D advective equation $\,u_{t}+u_{x}=0$ , with a step wave propagating to the right.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This loss of accuracy is to be expected due to Godunov's theorem.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The simulation was carried out with a mesh of 200 cells and used RK4 for time integration.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] MUSCL based numerical schemes extend the idea of using a linear piecewise approximation to each cell by using *slope limited* left and right extrapolated states.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The numerical fluxes $F_{i\pm 1/2}^{*}$ correspond to a nonlinear combination of first and second-order approximations to the continuous flux function.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The function $\phi \left(r_{i}\right)$ is a limiter function that limits the slope of the piecewise approximations to ensure the solution is TVD, thereby avoiding the spurious oscillations that would otherwise occur around discontinuities or shocks - see Flux limiter section.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The limiter is equal to zero when $r\leq 0$ and is equal to unity when $r=1$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Thus, the accuracy of a TVD discretization degrades to first order at local extrema, but tends to second order over smooth parts of the domain.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The algorithm is straight­forward to implement.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Once a suitable scheme for $F_{i+1/2}^{*}$ has been chosen, such as the *Kurganov and Tadmor scheme* (see below), the solution can proceed using standard numerical integration techniques.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] A precursor to the *Kurganov and Tadmor* (KT) *central scheme*, (Kurganov and Tadmor, 2000), is the *Nessyahu and Tadmor* (NT) a staggered *central scheme*, (Nessyahu and Tadmor, 1990).
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] It is a Riemann-solver-free, second-order, high-resolution scheme that uses MUSCL reconstruction.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] It is a fully discrete method that is straight­forward to implement and can be used on scalar and vector problems, and can be viewed as a Rusanov flux (also called the local Lax-Friedrichs flux) supplemented with high order reconstructions.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The algorithm is based upon central differences with comparable performance to Riemann type solvers when used to obtain solutions for PDE's describing systems that exhibit high-gradient phenomena.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The KT scheme extends the NT scheme and has a smaller amount of numerical viscosity than the original NT scheme.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] It also has the added advantage that it can be implemented as either a *fully discrete* or *semi-discrete* scheme.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Here we consider the semi-discrete scheme.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Beyond these CFL related speeds, no characteristic information is required.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The above flux calculation is most frequently called *Lax-Friedrichs flux* (though it's worth mentioning that such flux expression does not appear in Lax, 1954 but rather on Rusanov, 1961).
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] An example of the effectiveness of using a high resolution scheme is shown in the diagram opposite, which illustrates the 1D advective equation $u_{t}+u_{x}=0\$ , with a step wave propagating to the right.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The simulation was carried out on a mesh of 200 cells, using the Kurganov and Tadmor central scheme with Superbee limiter and used RK-4 for time integration.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This simulation result contrasts extremely well against the above first-order upwind and second-order central difference results shown above.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This scheme also provides good results when applied to sets of equations - see results below for this scheme applied to the Euler equations.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] However, care has to be taken in choosing an appropriate limiter because, for example, the Superbee limiter can cause unrealistic sharpening for some smooth waves.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The scheme can readily include diffusion terms, if they are present.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Full details of the algorithm (*full* and *semi-discrete* versions) and its derivation can be found in the original paper (Kurganov and Tadmor, 2000), along with a number of 1D and 2D examples.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Additional information is also available in the earlier related paper by Nessyahu and Tadmor (1990).
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] It is possible to extend the idea of linear extrapolation to higher-order reconstruction, and an example is shown in the diagram opposite.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] However, for this case the left and right states are estimated by interpolation of a second-order, upwind biased, difference equation.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This results in a parabolic reconstruction scheme that is third-order accurate in space.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] We follow the approach of Kermani (Kermani, et al., 2003), and present a third-order upwind biased scheme, where the symbols $u_{i+{\frac {1}{2}}}^{*}$ and $u_{i-{\frac {1}{2}}}^{*}$ again represent scheme dependent functions (of the limited reconstructed cell edge variables).
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] and the limiter function $\phi \left(r\right)\$ is the same as above.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Parabolic reconstruction is straight­forward to implement and can be used with the Kurganov and Tadmor scheme in lieu of the linear extrapolation shown above.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This has the effect of raising the spatial solution of the KT scheme to 3rd order.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] It performs well when solving the Euler equations, see below.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This increase in spatial order has certain advantages over 2nd order schemes for smooth solutions, however, for shocks it is more dissipative - compare diagram opposite with above solution obtained using the KT algorithm with linear extrapolation and Superbee limiter.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This simulation was carried out on a mesh of 200 cells using the same KT algorithm but with parabolic reconstruction.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Time integration was by RK-4, and the alternative form of van Albada limiter, $\phi _{va}(r)={\frac {2r}{1+r^{2}}}\$ , was used to avoid spurious oscillations.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] For simplicity we consider the 1D case without heat transfer and without body force.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] and where **${\mbox{U}}$** is a vector of states and **${\mbox{F}}$** is a vector of fluxes.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The equations above represent conservation of **mass**, **momentum**, and **energy**.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] There are thus three equations and four unknowns, $\rho$ (density) u (fluid velocity), p (pressure) and E (total energy).
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] where $e\$ represents specific internal energy.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] In order to close the system an equation of state is required.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] where $\gamma \$ is equal to the ratio of specific heats $\left[c_{p}/c_{v}\right]$ for the fluid.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] We can now proceed, as shown above in the simple 1D example, by obtaining the left and right extrapolated states for each state variable.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Similarly, for momentum $\rho u$ , and total energy E .
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Velocity u , is calculated from momentum, and pressure p , is calculated from the equation of state.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Having obtained the limited extrapolated states, we then proceed to construct the edge fluxes using these values.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The solution can now proceed by integration using standard numerical techniques.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The above illustrates the basic idea of the MUSCL scheme.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] However, for a practical solution to the Euler equations, a suitable scheme (such as the above KT scheme) also has to be chosen in order to define the function $\mathbf {F} _{i\pm {\frac {1}{2}}}^{*}$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The diagram opposite shows a 2nd order solution to G A Sod's shock tube problem (Sod, 1978) using the above high resolution Kurganov and Tadmor Central Scheme (KT) with Linear Extrapolation and Ospre limiter.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This illustrates clearly demonstrates the effectiveness of the MUSCL approach to solving the Euler equations.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The simulation was carried out on a mesh of 200 cells using Matlab code (Wesseling, 2001), adapted to use the KT algorithm and Ospre limiter.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Time integration was performed by a 4th order SHK (equivalent performance to RK-4) integrator.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The diagram opposite shows a 3rd order solution to G A Sod's shock tube problem (Sod, 1978) using the above high resolution Kurganov and Tadmor Central Scheme (KT) but with parabolic reconstruction and van Albada limiter.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] This again illustrates the effectiveness of the MUSCL approach to solving the Euler equations.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The simulation was carried out on a mesh of 200 cells using Matlab code (Wesseling, 2001), adapted to use the KT algorithm with Parabolic Extrapolation and van Albada limiter.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] The alternative form of van Albada limiter, $\phi _{va}(r)={\frac {2r}{1+r^{2}}}\$ , was used to avoid spurious oscillations.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Time integration was performed by a 4th order SHK integrator.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] Various other high resolution schemes have been developed that solve the Euler equations with good accuracy.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] More information on these and other methods can be found in the references below.
[src:finite-volume-method/muscl-scheme] An open source implementation of the Kurganov and Tadmor central scheme can be found in the external links below.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] A **Riemann solver** is a numerical method used to solve a hyperbolic partial differential equation based on the solution of the corresponding Riemann problem.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] They are heavily used in computational fluid dynamics and computational magnetohydrodynamics.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] Generally speaking, Riemann solvers are specific methods for computing the numerical flux across a discontinuity in the Riemann problem.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] They form an important part of high-resolution schemes; typically the right and left states for the Riemann problem are calculated using some form of nonlinear reconstruction, such as a flux limiter or a WENO method, and then used as the input for the Riemann solver.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] Godunov is credited with introducing the first exact Riemann solver for the Euler equations, by extending the previous CIR (Courant-Isaacson-Rees) method to non-linear systems of hyperbolic conservation laws.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] Modern solvers are able to simulate relativistic effects and magnetic fields.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] More recent research shows that an exact series solution to the Riemann problem exists, which may converge fast enough in some cases to avoid the iterative methods required in Godunov's scheme.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] As iterative solutions are too costly, especially in magnetohydrodynamics, some approximations have to be made.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] Roe used the linearisation of the Jacobian, which he then solves exactly.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] The HLLE solver (developed by Ami Harten, Peter Lax, Bram van Leer and B.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] Einfeldt) is an approximate solution to the Riemann problem, which is only based on the integral form of the conservation laws and the largest and smallest signal velocities at the interface.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] The HLLC (Harten-Lax-van Leer-Contact) solver was introduced by Toro.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] It restores the missing rarefaction wave by using an estimation technique, such as linearisation.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] More advanced techniques exist, like using the Roe average velocity for the middle wave speed.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] These schemes are quite robust and efficient but somewhat more diffusive.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] These solvers were introduced by Hiroaki Nishikawa and Kitamura, in order to overcome the carbuncle problems of the Roe solver and the excessive diffusion of the HLLE solver at the same time.
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] They developed robust and accurate Riemann solvers by combining the Roe solver and the HLLE/Rusanov solvers: they show that being applied in two orthogonal directions the two Riemann solvers can be combined into a single Roe-type solver (the Roe solver with modified wave speeds).
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] In particular, the one derived from the Roe and HLLE solvers, called Rotated-RHLL solver, is extremely robust (carbuncle-free for all possible test cases on both structured and unstructured grids) and accurate (as accurate as the Roe solver for the boundary layer calculation).
[src:finite-volume-method/riemann-solver] There are a variety of other solvers available, including more variants of the HLL scheme and solvers based on flux-splitting via characteristic decomposition.
[src:finite-volume-method/roe-solver] where A is the Jacobian matrix of the flux vector ${\boldsymbol {F}}({\boldsymbol {U}})$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/roe-solver] The Roe method consists of finding a matrix ${\tilde {A}}({\boldsymbol {U}}_{i},{\boldsymbol {U}}_{i+1})$ that is assumed constant between two cells.
[src:finite-volume-method/roe-solver] The Riemann problem can then be solved as a truly linear hyperbolic system at each cell interface.
[src:finite-volume-method/roe-solver] Phil Roe introduced a method of parameter vectors to find such a matrix for some systems of conservation laws.
[src:finite-volume-method/roe-solver] Once the Roe matrix corresponding to the interface between two cells is found, the intercell flux is given by solving the quasi-linear system as a truly linear system.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] In numerical methods, **total variation diminishing (TVD)** is a property of certain discretization schemes used to solve hyperbolic partial differential equations.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] The most notable application of this method is in computational fluid dynamics.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] The concept of TVD was introduced by Ami Harten.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] In Computational Fluid Dynamics, TVD scheme is employed to capture sharper shock predictions without any misleading oscillations when variation of field variable “ $\phi$ ” is discontinuous.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] To capture the variation fine grids ( $\Delta x$ very small) are needed and the computation becomes heavy and therefore uneconomic.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] The use of coarse grids with central difference scheme, upwind scheme, hybrid difference scheme, and power law scheme gives false shock predictions.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] TVD scheme enables sharper shock predictions on coarse grids saving computation time and as the scheme preserves monotonicity there are no spurious oscillations in the solution.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] where $\rho$ is the density, $\mathbf {u}$ is the velocity vector, $\phi$ is the property being transported, $\Gamma$ is the coefficient of diffusion and $S_{\phi }$ is the source term responsible for generation of the property $\phi$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] Here $\mathbf {n}$ is the normal to the surface of control volume.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] where U refers to upstream, $UU$ refers to upstream of U and D refers to downstream.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] Note that $f^{+}$ is the weighing function when the flow is in positive direction (i.e., from left to right) and $f^{-}$ is the weighing function when the flow is in the negative direction from right to left.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] If the flow is in positive direction then, Péclet number P is positive and the term $(P-|P|)=0$ , so the function $f^{-}$ won't play any role in the assumption of $\phi _{r}$ and $\phi _{l}$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] Likewise when the flow is in negative direction, P is negative and the term $(P+|P|)=0$ , so the function $f^{+}$ won't play any role in the assumption of $\phi _{r}$ and $\phi _{r}$ .
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] It therefore takes into account the values of property depending on the direction of flow and using the weighted functions tries to achieve monotonicity in the solution thereby producing results with no spurious shocks.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] Monotone schemes are attractive for solving engineering and scientific problems because they do not produce non-physical solutions.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] Godunov's theorem proves that linear schemes which preserve monotonicity are, at most, only first order accurate.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] Higher order linear schemes, although more accurate for smooth solutions, are not TVD and tend to introduce spurious oscillations (wiggles) where discontinuities or shocks arise.
[src:finite-volume-method/total-variation-diminishing] To overcome these drawbacks, various high-resolution, non-linear techniques have been developed, often using flux/slope limiters.
